output distributions¶

This project is unique compared to the others in that there are 2 outputs. Everyone working on this project must therefore fit models to predict two different responses. Everyone correctly visualized the output distributions in the proposal, but let's focus on those variables here. The cell below selects the two outputs, then reshapes the dataframe into long format via .melt(). Histograms are used to visualize the distributions of the outputs within separate facets below.

In [9]:
sns.displot(data = df.loc[:, ['mass', 'pressure']].reset_index().rename(columns={'index': 'rowid'}).copy().melt(id_vars='rowid'),
            x='value', col='variable', kind='hist',
            facet_kws={'sharex': False, 'sharey': False},
            common_bins = False)

plt.show()

As we see above the two distributions are NOT symmetric. Lack of symmetry or asymmetry is referred to as skew. A Gaussian distribution is symmetric. The long tails to the right side (higher values) in both distributions have less frequent values at very high values compared to the most probable values (represented by the histogram bin with the highest counts).

When we see that distributions have long tails, we need to consider if there is a natural bound associated with the variable. The .describe() method is used to print the summary statistics for both outputs below. The distribution on mass appears to be "pushed up" against zero. The .describe() method shows the minimum value is very small, $\approx 10^{-10}$, but is above zero.

Why are we paying so much attention to the minimum value? When we introduced the assumptions of linear regression, we focused on the sampling distribution of the output around the AVERAGE output. Regression models assume Gaussian distributions for the sampling distribution. A Gaussian distribution will not respect such a lower bound. This means a regression model can predict a negative number, and the confidence interval and especially the prediction interval can make it seem like negative values are possible.

This means when we fit regression models for outputs with bounds we must first transform the output. This way the model will always respect the lower bound of the variable.

There are multiple kinds of transformations we can use to accomplish this goal. A few simple transformations are natural log, log-base 10, and the square root. I commonly use natural log. More advanced transformations are power series transformations like Box-Cox (which requires all positive numbers) or the more general Yeo-Johnson (which handles negative and positive numbers). The more advanced approaches are discussed in CMPINF 2120.

Feel free to try out different transformations to get a feel for the influence of the transformation. Let's see what the natural log transformation does by calculating the natural log of mass within a copied dataframe.

In [25]:
df_copy = df.copy()

df_copy['log_mass'] = np.log( df_copy.mass )

As we see below, the distribution of log_mass is more symmetric. It is not Gaussian, but it is more Gaussian-like compared to the distribution of mass. The log_mass variable is now more appropriate to use for regression.

In [27]:
sns.displot(data = df_copy, x='log_mass')

plt.show()

Unfortunately, we cannot apply the natural log transformation directly to pressure. This is because pressure has the negative number and the natural log function can only be applied to positive numbers! As shown below, applying np.log() to df.pressure produces a warning message! The row with the negative pressure value is set to MISSING!

Applying the np.log() function therefore induces a MISSING into our data! One way to overcome this missing is to modify the transformation. Instead of applying np.log() as is, we can first ADD a number to "shift" the values to the right. This will cause the minimum value to greater than zero!

For example, adding 150 to pressure causes the minimum value to be above zero!

This "shift" approach seems like a hack. And in truth, it is. It is a simple way to apply overcome applying the log-transformation to negative numbers. It can be used when there is a small fraction of negative values and as we have seen, pressure has 1 and only 1 value less than zero. Thus, let's use this "hack" and define a new column pressure_shift which shifts pressure by 150.

In [31]:
df_copy['pressure_shift'] = df_copy.pressure + 150

Let's now apply the log-transformation! However, just to show a different function lets use log base 10, np.log10(), instead of the natural log, np.log().Feel free to try another transformation!

In [32]:
df_copy['log_pressure'] = np.log10( df_copy.pressure_shift )

The distribution of the log_pressure variable is shown below. The distribution resembles "half" of a Gaussian. The lowest histogram bin contains a single observation which corresponds to the original negative value! The transformation is now highlighting the single negative value from the rest of the observations! Is the log base 10 transformation the best here? Perhaps not, so try out other transformations to see the effect.

Cluster analysis¶

Most of the proposals used all variables, inputs and outputs together in the clustering. However, there are a few alternatives to consider when trying out clustering for a multiple output regression problem like this.

The first is to cluster based just on the inputs. After examining the input distributions associated with the identified clusters, examine the output distributions associated with each cluster. The clusters were based just on the inputs, and so it will be interesting to see which output values are associated with each cluster.

The second is to cluster based just on the outputs. After examining the output distributions associated with the identified clusters, examine the input distributions associated with each cluster. The clusters were based on the outputs, and so it will be interesting to see which inputs are associated with each cluster.

The two ways of formulating the cluster analysis are complimentary to each other. However, they are both trying to help us further examine the input-to-output relationship. That said, for this particular project, clustering the output together is the preferred approach. The reason why will be discussed in detail later in this report.

Clustering based on the outputs should be performed with the transformed output values rather than the original outputs. Many of the original output values "pile up" near the lower bound. Transforming the outputs "stretches" them and can allow the clustering to examine the behavior more evenly across the range of the output.

To help see why the transformations are useful, a scatter plot between the original outputs is shown below. The long-tails we saw in the marginal distributions are represented below by the points "far" away from the main grouping around 0.

In [44]:
sns.relplot(data = df, x='mass', y ='pressure')

plt.show()

The scatter plot between the log-transformed outputs is easier to look at. The markers are not piling up on one side. The observations are essentially spread out more evenly across the plot. Again, the negative pressure is highlighted as being quite different from the others!

sns.pairplot(data = df, vars=['r_barrel', 'r_vortex', 'h_vortex', 'w_inlet', 'h_inlet'])

plt.show()

The data in this project come from a designed experiment. The inputs were purposedly constructed to be uniformly spread across defined lower and upper bounds. The design purposedly had minimal input-to-input correlation and tried to "fill" the space as much as possible. This is why it is preferrable to cluster based on the outputs! The inputs were designed to have no clear structure. We therefore want to see if the output clusters can divide the input space into meaningful regions!

To help identify the "space filling" nature of the design, let's visualize all 5 inputs within a single graphic. No one was required to do this, but it can be useful to see.

We will visualize the relationship between r_barrel and r_vortex with a scatter plot. The three remaining inputs will be discretized based on the quartiles. The quartiles are the lines in a boxplot. Thus, the quartiles divide the variable into 4 "buckets" or bins of roughly equal number of observations.

Model fitting and predictions¶

In the final project, you must fit multiple models of varying complexity for each output. You have seen in lecture and in the homework assignments how to create various kinds of features from the inputs including additive features, interactions, polynomials, and applying other functions to the inputs. Your task will be to identify the best performing model for each output. You must then make predictions with your selected best models to visualize the trends of the outputs with respect to the inputs. Because you are fitting the models with the transformed output, you can visualize the trends in the transformed output space. This way you can easily include the confidence interval and prediction interval around the trend. Can you identify the input values that meet the original optimization objective of the project?

This project is a regression problem. However, if you want to work on a classification problem, you can convert the mass variable into a binary output based on if mass is greater than its median value. This way you will have one regression task to predict pressure (via the transformed pressure) and one binary classification task to classify if the mass is "high" or "low". A simple way to create the binary variable is with the np.where() function.

In [30]:
df_copy_b['bin_mass'] = np.where( df_copy_b.mass > df_copy_b.mass.median(), 1, 0 )

As shown below, we have a perfectly balanced binary outcome.

In [31]:
df_copy_b.bin_mass.value_counts(normalize=True)
Out[31]:
1    0.5
0    0.5
Name: bin_mass, dtype: float64

You are not required to work with the binary version of mass. This option is available if you would prefer to get practice with binary classification rather than working on 2 regression problems. If you take this approach, you must fit multiple binary classifiers, select the best one, and then predict the probability of the event. You must visualize the probability of the event with respect to the inputs to identify inputs that meet the original requirements of the optimization problem.

In [ ]:
